    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, keep an eye on those roots—they’re the real “goblin” behind the health of your fig. While you’re untangling, look for a few key signs that everything’s running smooth:\n\n- **Root density and color**: The roots should feel firm, plump, and a healthy light greenish‑brown. If you see any dark, mushy spots, that could mean a fungal issue or just a wet root ball that’s too heavy.  \n- **Root spread**: They should spread outward and a little downward, not just clump in the center. A good sign is that the roots are “fanning” out like a goblin’s fingers on a spell‑casting hand.  \n- **No exposed, dry roots**: When you loosen the root ball, you’ll want to avoid too many bare, dry strands. If you see a lot of exposed roots, it’s a good sign that the root ball is loose enough for the new pot.  \n- **Root “bunches”**: Look for small clusters of roots that are a bit thicker than the rest—these are your “goblin” roots that will do the heavy lifting in the new pot.\n\n**What to watch for during repot",
